<TEXT>
congress on friday approved a 32 billion 
budget for the district of columbia after attaching a strong 
antiabortion amendment and a measure allowing georgetown 
university to deny certain rights to gay groups prompting a threat 
by city officials to shut down the local government 
im not sure the outcome is in the best interests of this 
body the district of columbia or the country sen tom harkin 
diowa said as the senate approved the budget late friday night 
in the way the district spends its own money the congress need 
not be intervening 
the bill was sent to president reagan for his signature less 
than an hour before midnight when the new fiscal year began 
in approving the citys 32 billion fiscal year 1989 budget 
the house and senate added an amendment that would freeze the 537 
million federal payment for the districts budget and prevent the 
city from spending its own money if medicaidfunded abortions are 
performed on women whose lives are not threatened 
the spending bill also would allow georgetown university to go 
back on its agreement to allow gay student associations to meet on 
campus and apply for student government funds 
the roman catholic school had reached an agreement with the gay 
groups in march after the district of columbia superior court and 
court of appeals upheld a finding by the citys human rights office 
that georgetown was discriminating against gay groups georgetown 
officials have said that they will not go back on their agreement 
with the student groups regardless of what congress decided 
walter fauntroy the nonvoting democratic delegate to congress 
from the district was angered by the intrusion into local affairs 
and said he would encourage city officials to disobey the 
abortionfunding prohibition to trigger a congressionally mandated 
shutdown of city government such a move would leave congress with 
the responsibility of governing the nations capital 
you will forgive me having respected you for 18 years if i 
suggest to my mayor and people that work for this city government 
that maybe its time to end this facade a tearful fauntroy told 
his house colleagues in a meeting where the final touches were put 
on the budget if congress wants to decide every little detail 
maybe its time to do that 
david clarke chairman of the district of columbia council 
concurred with fauntroy saying i believe it is time for the 
people of the district of columbia to take to the streets to defend 
their constitutional rights 
the abortion measure offered by rep robert dornan rcalif 
toughens current legislation which allows the city to use locally 
generated funds for abortions and restricts federal funds for use 
by rape and incest victims women suffering through ectopic 
pregnancies or when the mothers life is threatened 
</TEXT>
