<TEXT>
the soviet union has been working 
quietly during the olympics to create a good image in this strongly 
anticommunist nation 
the soviets got an early start in their publicity campaign when 
they sent the bolshoi ballet the moscow philharmonic and an ethnic 
korean singer to seoul to perform in a cultural festival that 
preceded the sports competitions 
the performances were followed by nelli kim the former soviet 
gymnastic star of korean descent who came with the soviet athletes 
as a goodwill ambassador and gymnastics judge 
kim and some other ethnic koreans who were allowed to visit 
south korea for the first time were received with open arms 
the soviet union and south korea have no formal diplomatic or 
trade relations so the novelty of soviet visitors fanned the 
publics interest 
korean television devoted segments of nightly newscasts to the 
soviets showing kims activities interviews with a correspondent 
of the official communist party newspaper pravda and a visit to a 
typical korean family by reporters of the tass soviet news agency 
at a preliminary olympic soccer match between the united states 
and the soviet union last week some koreans cheered for the soviet 
side waving huge hammerandsickle red flags a scene almost 
impossible to imagine only a few months ago 
koreans also held up signs reading cccp the russian 
letters for ussr during the mens basketball game between the 
soviet union and the united states on wednesday the soviets upset 
the americans 8276 
korean media have mentioned a strong possibility of expanding 
cultural and commercial exchanges with the soviet union 
but despite the new developments relations between the south 
korean government and the soviet union are likely to remain cool 
because moscow supports communist north korea 
in addition south korea remains a firm ally of the united 
states which supported in the war with the north in the 1950s that 
divided the korean peninsula about 42000 american troops are 
stationed in the south 
