<TEXT>
housewives local fishermen and 
conservation officers worked frantically early today to save 39 
whales stranded on a remote beach on the west coast of australia 
they said 21 of the beached mammals had already died near 
augusta 150 miles south of perth in western australia 
the volunteers and others numbering about 100 people in all 
stroked the creatures and kept them moistened through the night to 
keep them alive 
the school of 60 false killer whales are believed to have 
beached themselves wednesday night at the scott river national 
park just east of augusta 
the department of conservation and land management rushed 
experts to the beach after the whales were found thursday afternoon 
scattered along a five mile stretch of beach volunteers soon 
joined the rescue effort 
augusta postmaster gary nash said it will be a tough battle 
because access to the beach was hampered by thick forests 
many of the whales were battered by heavy surf this morning 
while others were several yards up the beach and partly covered in 
sand 
dave mell chief wildlife officer for the department said they 
wanted to move the 39 stricken whales six miles west to a sheltered 
inlet and then lead them out to sea 
augusta was the site of a dramatic rescue operation in july 1986 
when 140 false killer whales stranded themselves at another beach 
near the town 
that rescue operation involving hundreds of volunteers saved 
all but a handful of the whales and captured worldwide headlines 
mell said it was hoped front end loaders and fourwheeldrive 
vehicles would be able to transport the whales along the beach but 
he said sections of the sand were soft and tricky for vehicles 
some of the whales look remarkably good and have weathered the 
trauma of coming ashore quite well he said some perished soon 
after stranding 
one thing in our favour is the weather its cold and they need 
to be keep wet and cool 
volunteers braved cold conditions to stay with the stranded 
whales through the night with groups adopting individual 
animals 
mell cautioned that the whales would drown if they were unable 
to stay upright in the heavy surf or if they overheated because 
they were out of the water 
the cause of the mass beaching is not known 
