the state department said friday all parties 
to peace negotiations in southwest africa are in agreement that a 
timetable for the withdrawal of cuban troops from angola is 
obtainable 
in an upbeat account of four days of talks this week in the 
congolese capital of brazzaville deputy spokeswoman phyllis oakley 
said the process has reached a crucial and likely final phase 
the timetable for the withdrawal of the more than 50000 cuban 
troops has been the most difficult issue in the negotiations since 
they began in their present form last may with the united states 
serving as mediator officials from south africa cuba and angola 
have held seven rounds of talks 
the new york times reported in fridays editions that the 
parties agreed in principal to a 24month withdrawal timetable 
mrs oakley declined to give specifics but her wording 
indicated that the parties are working on a compromise that would 
permit the cubans to remain on longer than the time period sought 
by south africa 
in return the cubans would redeploy their forces away from the 
southern regions of angola the stronghold of the americanbacked 
anticommunist rebel movement 
this is a complex matter in that it involves fixing not only 
the final deadline for the departure of all cuban troops but also 
schedules for their phased redeployment and withdrawal prior to 
that deadline mrs oakley said 
initially south africa with us support had insisted on a 
cuban withdrawal that would coincide with unsupervised elections 
for namibia a process which could begin nov 1 and end with the 
installation of the territorys first independent government in 
1989 south africa has administered namibia for 73 years 
cuba has been holding out for a longer withdrawal period 
apparently concerned that the promarxist government may not be 
able to cope with the powerful rebel movement 
mrs oakley suggested that differences over the timetable have 
narrowed 
all parties perceive that agreement on a timetable for cuban 
troop withdrawal from angola is obtainable she said she also 
suggested that some tentative decisions have been reached by the 
negotiators which require final approval of their respective 
governments 
the negotiations have reached the point at which all parties 
understand the final decisions they must make to achieve an 
agreement she said 
these decisions which affect vital national interests and 
security concerns can only be made at the highest levels of 
government in havana luanda and pretoria 
