<TEXT>
here are thumbnail sketches of the top soviet 
officials at the center of mikhail s gorbachevs shakeup of the 
kremlin hierarchy 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
andrei a gromyko resigned his politburo post friday after 15 
years as a full member gromyko 79 assumed the largely ceremonial 
post of president four months after gorbachev became general 
secretary in march 1985 during his 28 years as foreign minister 
gromyko dubbed old stone face for his dour expression was 
widely respected for his negotiating ability and his grasp of 
international affairs his official duties as president mainly 
involved protocol functions but he remained an influential 
politburo member it was said to be his vote that broke a tie in 
the politburo and elected gorbachev party leader but his influence 
appeared to wane under gorbachev at the june party conference a 
delegate said gromyko was not fit to hold office because of his 
inability to work under gorbachevs reforms trained as an 
economist gromyko served in the soviet embassy in washington under 
josef stalin and became foreign minster under nikita s khrushchev 
mikhail s solomentsev regarded as an expert on heavy 
industry was retired from his positions as a full politburo member 
and head of the party control commission charged with 
investigating reports of corruption by party officials at the june 
party conference a delegate said solomentsev 75 should retire 
because he could not work under gorbachevs reforms solomentsev 
headed a commission reviewing rehabilitation of victims of stalins 
repression he was born into a peasant family worked in 
agriculture and industry and was appointed a nonvoting member of 
the politburo in 1971 it was more than a decade before he was 
elevated to full member while a nonvoting politburo member 
solomentsev was premier of the russian republic the largest of the 
soviet unions 15 republics 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
anatoly f dobrynin dobrynin 68 ambassador to washington for 
24 years was sent into retirement after having served since 1986 
as communist party central committee secretary for foreign affairs 
he was dean of the washington diplomatic corps at the end of his 
tenure in washington which spanned the administrations of six 
presidents and shattered the stereotype of dour soviet envoys 
malcolm toon former us ambassador to moscow called dobrynin 
one of the ablest diplomats of the 20th century dobrynin son 
of a plumber was an aeronautical engineer in world war ii his 
english studies paved the way for a diplomatic career he went to 
washington in 1952 as an embassy counselor returned to moscow in 
1960 and went back to washington two years later 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
vladimir i dolgikh a candidate member of the politburo since 
may 1982 dolgikh 63 was retired from the job to which he was 
appointed by president leonid i brezhnev six months before 
brezhnevs death dolgikh first gained attention as head of the 
norilsk mining complex in northern siberia during the 1960s he 
earned the reputation of a good industrial manager and was in 
charge of heavy industry in his later role on the politburo when 
ethnic unrest erupted this year in armenia dolgikh was among those 
sent there by moscow to try to ease tensions he left norilsk in 
1969 to become district head of the communist party in krasnoyarsk 
in 1971 he was named to the central committe and in 1976 became 
head of the central committees heavy industry department 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
pyotr n demichev demichev 70 a nonvoting politburo member 
for 24 years also was retired he had held the largely ceremonial 
job as deputy to gromyko since his removal in 1986 as culture 
minister he exerted a conservative influence on the arts during 
his 12 years as minister his shift from that position was regarded 
as a move by gorbachev to allow greater openness demichev earned a 
reputation in the 1950s as an authority on ideology for his 
involvement in city and neighborhood propaganda departments and as 
an experienced industrial manager like dolgikh demichev was sent 
to armenia to smooth ethnic tensions but overall his role was 
greatly reduced after gorbachev rose to power 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
vadim a medvedev medvedev was named a full member of the 
politburo two years after being chosen a full member of the central 
committee bypassing candidate membership little is known about 
the medvedev 59 an engineer and economist and a former rector of 
the academy of social sciences in the central committee he was an 
assistant professor at the leningrad institute of rail transport 
and in 1968 was elected secretary of the citys communist party 
committee from 1978 to 1983 he was a deputy head of the central 
committees propaganda department he gained full membership in the 
central committee in february 1986 a month later he was named 
secretary for science and education 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
alexandra p biryukova her appointment to the politburo as a 
nonvoting member makes her the first woman to hold such a high 
post since former culture minister yekaterina furtseva a full 
member from 1957 to 1961 a former trade union official biryukova 
59 has served as central committee secretary in charge of light 
industry and consumer goods since 1986 born in the moscow area 
she became a shop forewoman at a fabric plant in 1952 joined the 
party in 1956 and moved steadily up within the trade union ranks to 
become deputy chairman of the central council of trade unions in 
1985 to 1986 she became a full member of the central committee in 
1976 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
anatoly i lukyanov lukyanov 58 was chief of the central 
committees general department until his appointment as a 
nonvoting member of the politburo the general staff is the 
politburos administrative arm and all secret documents must pass 
through the department lukyanov graduated in 1953 with a law 
degree from moscow state university and was chief consultant of the 
council of ministers or cabinet legal commission from 1956 to 
1961 from 1969 to 1976 he was deputy chief of the supreme 
soviets department of soviet activities and in 1977 became chief 
of the presidiums secretariat his new responsibilities are 
uncertain 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
alexander v vlasov vlasov elevated to nonvoting status on 
