receive passports to travel abroad 
he had announced the amnesty proposal sept 7 
mti said the presidential council elected by parliament and 
exercises the functions of parliament between quarterly sessions 
passed at its friday meeting a statutory provision on granting 
pardons to those convicted of crimes between oct 23 1956 and may 
1 1957 
the revolt began oct 23 1956 with mass demonstrations for a 
new government and demands that soviet troops leave hungary on 
nov 4 200000 soviet troops and 2500 tanks struck at budapest to 
put down the uprising 
the amnesty covers those sentenced to prison for crimes against 
the state or for counterrevolutionary activities and people 
whose death penalty was commuted to imprisonment mti said 
the report said the amnesty does not extend to those convicted 
of high treason or espionage or those who in cumulation of 
offenses committed homicide robbery and caused public danger 
the minister of justice however would look into the cases of 
those who were excluded and in justified cases could ask the 
presidential council to grant individual pardons until nov 30 
1988 mti said 
