<TEXT>
when he led the cia during the ford 
administration vice president george bush battled the justice 
department in an effort to restrict a criminal investigation of 
senior cia officials a published report said 
at the time a federal grand jury was investigating allegations 
that officials working for or with the cia including former cia 
director richard helms lied under oath to congress about cia 
operations in chile during the early 1970s 
information about the dispute between bush the justice 
department and the ford white house staff came from newly released 
files in the gerald r ford presidential library in ann arbor 
mich the los angeles times reported in its friday editions 
the files showed that in october 1976 citing the need to 
protect intelligence sources bush repeatedly sought to prevent 
some documents from being declassified and cia witnesses from being 
called before a federal grand jury 
when white house officials reminded bush that president ford had 
already given a public pledge that his administration would not use 
classification or any other means to prevent exposure of illegal 
activities bush balked according to the files 
an impasse exists between the justice department and director 
george bush of the cia white house counsel philip w buchen 
wrote to ford 
buchen told the president that if the justice department failed 
to obtain the disputed information it would abort the pending 
investigation and lead to no prosecution 
in a memo at the time to another white house official bush 
said there is no intention on my part or on the part of this 
agency to take any action that might reasonably be construed as an 
effort to thwart or frustrate the investigation being conducted by 
the justice department 
at the same time i mean to do whatever is necessary and 
appropriate to carry out my statutory mandate to protect 
intelligence sources and methods believing as i do that such 
protection is at the heart of the agencys ability to function 
effectively he said 
president ford instructed bush to let federal prosecutors have 
what they needed 
the justice department investigation eventually resulted in 
helms 1977 plea of no contest to two criminal charges of failing 
to testify fully completely and accurately to congress 
craig fuller bushs chief of staff said through a spokeswoman 
he would withhold comment until seeing the documents spokesman 
mark goodin told the associated press late friday he could not 
comment until he had read the report 
