<TEXT>
in vetoing the textile protection bill president 
reagan might have reopened one of the most divisive and emotional 
issues between liberals and conservatives 
the issue is bound to play a major role in the presidential 
debates because it is one that interests almost everyone oddly it 
is also one on which many people seem unable to make up their minds 
one side believes religiously that to protect textiles is to 
protect jobs the other believes it costs jobs one side believes 
protection is a prop to the american economy the other says it 
costs every american dearly 
it is a regional issue as well since many of the textile jobs 
that would be protected by import limitations are in the south but 
there is another side of the job picture it might cost jobs in the 
north and elsewhere 
the bill vetoed by the president would have further limited 
textile apparel and footwear imports already strongly protected 
in fact it is sometimes said that no other country has a bigger 
tariff wall 
the issue is loaded with misconceptions the very largest of 
them being one held over for decades including the 1930s when the 
textile industry was indeed in trouble but it is far less troubled 
today 
edward l hudgins of the heritage foundation a 
conservativeoriented think tank that often takes a probusiness 
position recently issued a paper stating that the american 
textile and apparel industry clearly is an industry that doesnt 
need help 
the industry he states is working at near maximum capacity 
95 percent compared with the mid80s for all domestic 
manufacturing it is using more wool cotton and manmade fibers 
than ever before employment is up 21000 new jobs were added last 
year textile profits are up as well so are exports 
lets keep it that way say those who view a healthy textile 
industry as necessary for certain regional economies times were 
not always good in fact they say they were dismal until 
protection put the industry on its feet 
perhaps say the freetraders but consider the cost hudgins 
says american consumers pay between 25 billion and 30 billion 
annually in higher prices due to these restrictions 
in addition there may be a cost to nontextile areas in jobs 
nancy oliver policy analyst at citizens for a sound economy 
another conservative think tank contends that textile 
protectionism costs more jobs than it saves 
the legislation just vetoed she says would have protected 
fewer than 46700 textile apparel and footwear jobs but would 
have destroyed more than 52400 retailing jobs that depend on 
imports 
she estimates the protection price tag for each of these 46700 
jobs could be as much as 262000 a year a figure so enormous it 
provokes comparison with the 17000 average annual pay scale for 
each job a bad bargain she suggests 
such arguments however may be ignored when the debate is 
graphically and personally described a job lost anywhere and 
jobs are lost in areas where textile companies falter is an 
upsetting experience for other americans 
a feeling of patriotism also enters the debate especially when 
americans sense they are being exploited by lowwage foreign 
manufacturers a feeling of brotherhood exists not just on the 
part of workers but employers too 
high as the cost might be therefore it is conceivable that 
many americans might be willing to pay the price of protectionism 
so long as the dollar total remains obscured by other parts of the 
debate 
