<TEXT>
at an average perroom price of 613000 room 
service not included the sale of the posh intercontinental chain 
is just the latest in a series of deluxe hotel properties to be 
snapped up at top dollar 
the purchaser japans seibu saison group is in fine company 
last year the sultan of brunei paid 757000 a room for his name 
to appear on the deed to the beverly hills hotel affectionately 
dubbed the pink palace by the polo crowd and real estate 
developer donald trump added new yorks french renaissancestyle 
plaza hotel to his glitzy empire for an average 495000 a room 
earlier this year 
the prices seem preposterous to industry observers 
its just off the chart said joseph j doyle a senior vice 
president at the investment firm smith barney harris upham amp co 
referring to the 227 billion that seibu will pay in cash for 
the 100hotel intercontinental chain 
doyle estimated the chain will make just 90 million this year 
putting the sale price at an astronomical 25 times net income a 
more reasonable multiple would be 10 or 18 times net doyle said 
the chains occupancy rate is unimpressively average at about 70 
percent and while its flagship hotels namely the recently 
refurbished willard in washington san franciscos mark hopkins 
and the mayfair in london are unmistakably luxurious doyle said 
most others in the chain cater more to the businessman than the 
carriage trade 
what may be most attractive about the chain is that it is 
international in scope 
theres a scarcity of luxury international hotel chains in 
general and those that do exist are seldom offered for sale 
said thomas mcconnell a manager of the hotel consulting group at 
the accounting firm laventhol amp horwath 
investors who purchase a chain buy into a wellrounded business 
with wide expansion possibilities while those like trump who buy 
single hotels are far more limited in what they can do to develop 
the operation 
but if buyers are unhappy hotels generally are easy to sell 
when allegis corp announced last year it would sell its westin 
hotel chain which included the plaza buyers from around the 
world rushed to make bids 
the chain went to aoki corp of japan and the robert m bass 
group of texas for 2 billion allegis also sold its hilton 
international chain to britains ladbroke group plc for 107 
billion 
also enhancing their value toptier hotels are almost certain 
to sit on valuable real estate which is destined to appreciate 
over time 
another longerterm dimension that buyers may be looking 
toward is if the world should get back to a high inflationary 
environment these hotels would be a hedge their earnings would 
grow rapidly doyle said 
but perhaps most important is the intangible aura of status that 
comes with owning a luxury hotel these buyers want trophies 
doyle said 
indeed mcconnell said theres a lot of panache to owning a 
hotel you can put your name on it you can bring your friends 
there you can live there 
to underscore the interest people have in the industry 
mcconnell noted that there is even a tv show about a hotel you 
dont see a tv show called malls he said 
whether a hotel is profitable depends on its occupancy rate and 
its average room price few properties make money on the food they 
serve no matter how pricey 
luxury hotels whose rates typically start at 200 a night in 
major cities have the benefit of a high degree of repeat 
customers people are willing to pay a luxury rate because they 
want to see a certain level of service over and over again 
mcconnell said 
